Articles.Content: Dang I just came back to KSP after a break only to find that there has been a bug fix and now several mods are not working again (or at least are not on CKAN, this is not a complaint). Can I use the Github version/space dock version in 1.2.1?

23 minutes ago, Alexology said:

Dang I just came back to KSP after a break only to find that there has been a bug fix and now several mods are not working again (or at least are not on CKAN, this is not a complaint). Can I use the Github version/space dock version in 1.2.1? 

This version works fine for me. Most mods still work fine, they just need to be updated to say they work for the new update.

Use on your own risk, obviously. But it's not a very big change.

Quick question-

Do I need to start a new career to use this mod?  I am currently about ~30 hours into my current career and have unlocked 1/3 of the tech tree.  What would happen if I installed this mod?  Would it break my save?

Many thanks for your work!

1 hour ago, ble210 said:

Quick question-

Do I need to start a new career to use this mod?  I am currently about ~30 hours into my current career and have unlocked 1/3 of the tech tree.  What would happen if I installed this mod?  Would it break my save?

Many thanks for your work!

It shouldn't break the save. The only thing it could do is make some parts you have already unlocked locked again which could make it harder if you're playing with limited funds and have to buy researched parts before you can use them.

20 minutes ago, HoveringKiller said:

It shouldn't break the save. The only thing it could do is make some parts you have already unlocked locked again which could make it harder if you're playing with limited funds and have to buy researched parts before you can use them. 

Awesome, thank you!

3 hours ago, HoveringKiller said:

It shouldn't break the save. The only thing it could do is make some parts you have already unlocked locked again which could make it harder if you're playing with limited funds and have to buy researched parts before you can use them. 

(@ble210) And that's only if you're playing with extra-parts mods (or mods that move stock parts around in the tree).  CTT doesn't change any of the stock tech nodes, it only adds new ones for mods to put their parts in.

I am using the latest version on 1.2.1 an all parts in non-stock nodes have vanished. I have hide empty nodes installed so it's not like the parts are gone. They just don't show in the techtree nodes. Is this a known problem? Log below.

How do you add costum Nodes? I see how to add parts to a node but I did not see instructions to make a new node itself. I want to add a weapons branch for BDAc and other weapon mods.

14 hours ago, Vjrcr said:

How do you add costum Nodes? I see how to add parts to a node but I did not see instructions to make a new node itself. I want to add a weapons branch for BDAc and other weapon mods.

You need to make a Module Manager patch.

MM File Tutorial

You can see a lot of examples of custom node creating and editing in GameData/CommunityTechTree/Tree/CommunityTechTree.cfg. (If opening with Notepad looks weird, try downloading and using Notepad++)

For you specifically, you can follow this example if you're not familiar with MM patches:

Spoiler

We want to add a new node in the Heat Management branch of the CTT between the Heat Management Systems node and Advanced Heat Management node. Now, it looks like this:

    

We want it to look like this:

    

So we'll first add our node, then change the parent for Advanced Heat Management so it connects to our node instead of Heat Management systems. In an empty text file with any ".cfg" name (such as "My_CTT.cfg") we write: 


@TechTree:FOR[zzz]
{
	// Add our new node between Heat Management Systems and Advanced Heat Management.
	RDNode
	{
		id = improvedHeatManagement
		title = Improved Heat Management
		description = Be creative!
		cost = 300
		hideEmpty = False
		nodeName = my_improvedHeatManagement
		anyToUnlock = True
		icon = CommunityTechTree/UI/ctt_icon_heatManagementSystems
		pos = -1309,380,-1
		scale = 0.6
		Parent
		{
			parentID = heatManagementSystems
			lineFrom = RIGHT
			lineTo = LEFT
		}
	}

	// Delete parent for Advanced Heat Management, add parent for our node.
	@RDNode:HAS[#id[advHeatManagement]]
	{
		!Parent {}
		Parent
		{
			parentID = improvedHeatManagement
			lineFrom = RIGHT
			lineTo = LEFT
		}
	}
}

Some key info about MM patchs.

1) "@" edits a node or item. "%" edits nodes/items if they already exist, or creates them if they don't.

2) "!" or "-" deletes a node or item.

3) If you want to delete a node, you need to remember to put "{ }" after the node. If you want to delete an item, you need to remember to put " = dummy"

Example: "!Parent { }" for the Parent nodes, or "!parentID = dummy" for the parent id item.

4) If you want to delete only one parent, for example the second parent use indexes like "!Parent,1 { }". Indexes start from 0, so the second parent has index 1. Or I think you can use the parentID name like "!Parent[heatManagementSystems] { }".

5) I put ":FOR[zzz]" after "@TechTree" because MM changes things alphabetically, and I want my change to come last. You could also use ":FINAL". This is usually not recommended for community MM patches, but since these are your (the player's) personal changes, it's okay.

6) Spelling, capitalization, and closing your brackets { } are VERY important. If something doesn't work, your problem is probably one of these three things.

7) Order doesn't matter for tech tree changes. If you wanted to delete the parents for Advanced Heat Management and add our node as a parent first, you can do that.

8) MM patches should go into GamaDate or any folder in GameData.

Notes about nodes:

1) All nodes at the same Y position should have the same science cost. But that's ultimately up to you.

2) Node icons can be found in GameData/CommunityTechTree/UI, or GameData/Squad/PartList/SimpleIcons. Other mods might have more icons somewhere.
